{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"65e485d6-4e41-4025-935e-0396b451ee98","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool to NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key steps\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — this is the critical property that makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (defaults to the assembly name if omitted).\n3. **Pack it:** `dotnet pack -c Release`\n4. **Publish it:** `dotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg --api-key YOUR_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json`\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's it — no special packaging beyond `PackAsTool`. The stdio transport works naturally since the tool runs as a console app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9d89c8ea-acbe-4887-9f43-f65d7542246d","outputTokens":450,"requestId":"CBC1:6ABDE:18EA147:1C2DCAF:69FE899D"},"id":"befedfa1-305b-4586-afe4-a93b4c99382d","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:11:01.450Z","parentId":"70b01a97-f57c-437c-8b5b-1b0aabf66699"}
